loc_desc: Peggy Kuntz recalls growing up near the Lehigh Coal Mine.
Notes/description: Peg talks about the shack where she and her family lived at the Lehigh coal mine and how when her Dad came home from the mine she would play with him and get covered in coal dust

loc_desc: Peggy Kuntz recalls her childhood experience attending a rural school.
Notes/description: Peg talks about her experience in rural school (1st-5th grade)

loc_desc: Steve Lech recalls life on the Lech Farmstead.
Notes/description: Homestead history, family immigration story, early memories on the farm in Gladstone
Steve describes how rural the town of Dickinson used to be

latitude: Don't add this one to the map for now
loc_desc: Mary Ann Unruh tells the story of Pauline Crawley, a pioneering woman.
Notes/description: Pauline Crowley emigrated from PA by herself in early 20th century to homestead the Crowley ranch which later became the Unruh ranch. Mary Ann talks about Pauline's story and how hard the early homesteaders had it
Great Depression years on the farm, people in town went hungry but they always had food from the farm. Bath time, family life at the farm
Blizzard of 1966; doctors had to come to patients on snowmobiles

loc_desc: Evelyn Jensen describes the distance from Daglum to Dickinson.
Notes/description: Story about her uncle, as a young boy, suffering from appendicitis, because Daglum was so far from the hospital and because the roads were not good, he died on the way to the hospital.

loc_desc: Evelyn Jensen tells her family's story of immigration from Norway and settling in Southwestern North Dakora.
tags: Immigration, Norwegians, Homestead, Sod House, Kit House
Notes/description: Story about her paternal family immigrating from Norway, settling in Hettinger County, building the sod house and later replacing it with a kit house

Notes/description: Story about her and her sister making hay

loc_desc: Geneva Steier explains that many of the children of German-Russian families had to learn English in school.
